      "content": "From a strict, universal human rights perspective, the humanitarian asylum argument has a stronger initial foothold because the right to life and freedom from persecution is widely considered a non-negotiable moral prerequisite. A nation's right to control its borders, while sovereign, is often seen as subordinate to the right of an individual to safety when facing imminent danger. However, you can counter this by arguing that unchecked border crossings place undue strain on societal systems, raising moral questions about the duty of the receiving nation to maintain a functional society for all.",
